04276nam a22006495i 9780300129434DE-B159720200424112023.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200424t20082008ctu    fo  d z      eng d  a97803001294347 a10.12987/97803001294342doi  a(DE-B1597)484969  a(OCoLC)952732237  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  actucUS-CT 4aJC179b.R7 2002eb 7aPHI0190002bisacsh04a320/.012211 aRousseau, Jean-Jacques, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Social Contract and The First and Second Discourses /cJean-Jacques Rousseau; Susan Dunn. 1aNew Haven, CT : bYale University Press, c[2008] 4c©2008  a1 online resource (328 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aRethinking the Western Tradition00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction: Rousseau's Political Triptych -- tChronology of Rousseau's Life -- tRousseau, Cultural Critic0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aJean-Jacques Rousseau's ideas about society, culture, and government are pivotal in the history of political thought. His works are as controversial as they are relevant today. This volume brings together three of Rousseau's most important political writings-The Social Contract and The First Discourse (Discourse on the Sciences and Arts) and The Second Discourse (Discourse on the Origin and Foundations of Inequality)-and presents essays by major scholars that shed light on the dimensions and implications of these texts.Susan Dunn's introductory essay underlines the unity of Rousseau's political thought and explains why his ideas influenced Jacobin revolutionaries in France but repelled American revolutionaries across the ocean. Gita May's essay discusses Rousseau as cultural critic. Robert N. Bellah explores Rousseau's attempt to resolve the tension between the individual's desire for freedom and the obligations that society imposes. David Bromwich analyzes Rousseau as a psychologist of the human self. And Conor Cruise O'Brien takes on the "noxious," "deranged" Rousseau, excoriated by Edmund Burke but admired by Robespierre and Thomas Jefferson. Written from different, even opposing perspectives, these lucid essays convey a sense of the vital and contentious debate surrounding Rousseau and his legacy.For this edition Susan Dunn has provided a new translation of the Discourse on the Sciences and Arts and has revised a previously published translation of The Social Contract.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aCivilizationvEarly works to 1800. 0aCivilizationxEarly works to 1800. 0aPolitical sciencevEarly works to 1800. 0aPolitical sciencexEarly works to 1800. 0aSocial contractvEarly works to 1800. 0aSocial contractxEarly works to 1800. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Political.2bisacsh1 aBellah, Robert N.1 aBromwich, David1 aDunn, Susan, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMay, Gita1 aO´Brien , Conor Cruise08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYUP eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066772108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press eBook Package 2000-2013z978311053799440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300129434423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780300129434.jpg  a978-3-11-053799-4  Yale University Press eBook Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-066772-1  YUP eBook-Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles